06555nam a22007575i 9780226535067DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20071984ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226535067  a(DE-B1597)535838  a(OCoLC)1135588620  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHC106.3 HC110.I5aHC110.I5 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a330 s 339.5/22a339.52200aEconomic Transfers in the United States /ced. by Marilyn Moon. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2007] 4c©1984  a1 online resource (398 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Studies in Income and Wealth ;v4900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Transfers in a Total Incomes System of Accounts -- t2. An Accounting Framework for Transfer Payments and Its Implications for the Size Distribution of Income -- t3. Transfer Elements in the Taxation of Income from Capital -- t4. Approaches to Measuring and Valuing In-Kind Subsidies and the Distribution of Their Benefits -- t5. The Effect of Different Measures of Benefit on Estimates of the Distributive Consequences of Government Programs -- t6. The Role of Time in the Measurement of Transfers and Well-Being -- t7. Income Transfers and the Economic Status of the Elderly -- t8. The Role of Income Transfers in Reducing Inequality between and within Regions -- t9. Trends in Social Security Wealth by Cohort -- t10. Raising the Normal Retirement Age under Social Security: A Life-Cycle Analysis -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years the definition of an economic transfer—a payment to an individual or institution that does not arise out of current productive activity—has been subject to even wider interpretation. This volume addresses that trend and introduces new methods of measuring transfers in the American economy. Social security, private pension benefits, housing, and health care are traditional kinds of transfers. Accurate measurements of the degree and effect of these and of other, newly interpreted transfers are vital to economic policy making. Though this volume is not directly concerned with policy-making issues, it does impinge on many areas of current public concern; methods of transfer valuation, for example, may affect how we view the status of the aged. Researchers, policy analysts, and those who compile statistics on which social programs are based on will value the diverse approaches of these ten papers and their accompanying comments. Taken together the essays give great insight into the complexities of defining transfers and provide a wealth of new analytic methods. They were developed from material presented at the Income and Wealth Conference on Social Accounting for Transfers held at Madison, Wisconsin, in 1982.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIncome distributionzUnited States. 0aTransfer paymentszUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aeconomics, economy, economic transfer, payment, current productive activity, united states of america, american society, usa, transfers, social security, private pension benefits, housing, houses, healthcare, home ownership, policy making, valuation, income distribution, 20th century, retirement, government programs, taxes, taxation, capital.1 aBetson, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBudd, Edward C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkhauser, Richard V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanziger, Sheldon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisner, Robert, econtrib